'''Timothy John Payne''' (born 10 January 1994) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defender (association football)|defender]] for [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]] in the [[A-League]] and for the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=FIFA U-20 World Cup Colombia 2011 – List of Players|url=http://www.fifadata.com/document/FWYC/2011/pdf/FWYC_2011_SquadLists.pdf|publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA)|page=18|date=10 August 2011|accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref>

A noted [[utility player (association football)|utility player]], Payne has played almost every outfield position during his career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/118563561/all-whites-defender-tim-payne-extends-wellington-phoenix-stay|title = Wellington Phoenix utility Tim Payne negotiates his own contract extension|date = 3 January 2020}}</ref>

==Club career==

===Auckland City and Waitakere United===
Born in [[Auckland]], Payne attended [[Sacred Heart College, Auckland|Sacred Heart College]] and started his youth career with [[ASB Premiership]] club [[Auckland City FC]] before switching to play for rivals [[Waitakere United]]. Payne played a major role in Waitakere United's success in the ASB National Youth League in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Q & A WITH TIM PAYNE|url=http://www.waitakereunited.co.nz/041111.html|publisher=Waitakere United|date=3 November 2011|accessdate=18 January 2012}}</ref>

===Blackburn Rovers===
After impressing at the [[2011 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] Payne trialled with [[Premier League]] side [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] and then spent several months training at the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12874/7327269/|title=Kiwi set for Blackburn chance|date=23 November 2011|publisher=Sky Sports|accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> Days after celebrating his 18th birthday Payne signed a two-and-a-half-year contract with Rovers in January 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12875/7438374/|title=Payne seals Rovers move|date=17 January 2012|publisher=Sky Sports|accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> Due to work permit issues that prevented him from playing for Rovers, he was released at the end of his contract.

===Wellington Phoenix===
In July 2019, Payne signed a one-year contract with [[A-League]] side [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wellingtonphoenix.com/news/wellington-phoenix-sign-kiwi-international|title=Wellington Phoenix Sign Kiwi International|website=Wellington Phoenix|date=19 July 2019|language=en|access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref> Payne made his A-League debut for the Phoenix in the first match of the [[2019–20 Wellington Phoenix FC season|2019–20 season]] in a 0–1 defeat against [[Western United FC|Western United]] on 13 October 2019 — Payne was substituted in for [[Louis Fenton]] in the 68th minute.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/wellington-phoenix-take-positives-opening-day-loss/|title=Wellington Phoenix Take Positives from Opening Day Loss|date=13 October 2019|access-date=29 May 2026|website={{A-League team|WP}}}}</ref> On 3 January 2020, it was announced that Payne had signed a two-year contract extension with the Phoenix.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/118563561/all-whites-defender-tim-payne-extends-wellington-phoenix-stay|title=Wellington Phoenix utility Tim Payne negotiates his own contract extension|first=Phillip|last=Rollo|newspaper=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|date=3 January 2020}}</ref> On 10 June 2020, Payne pleaded guilty to a drink-driving charge after a shirtless late-night joy ride in a golf cart in Sydney while the team was supposed to be in self-isolation. He was subsequently ordered by the court to pay a AUS$700 fine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/121790357/wellington-phoenix-defender-tim-payne-pleads-guilty-to-drinkdriving-after-golf-cart-ride|title=Wellington Phoenix defender Tim Payne pleads guilty to drink-driving after golf cart ride|first=Andrew|last=Voerman|newspaper=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|date=11 June 2020}}</ref>

On 4 November 2023, in his 93rd appearance for the Phoenix, Payne scored his first goal for the club following an overlapping run and a well-taken finish with his weaker left foot. The Phoenix defeated [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]] 5–2 at [[Wellington Regional Stadium|Sky Stadium]], [[Wellington]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/301004039/tim-payne-right-back-to-his-best-for-wellington-phoenix|title=Tim Payne right back to his best for Wellington Phoenix|date=7 November 2023|access-date=29 May 2026|website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|first=Phillip|last=Rollo}}</ref> Payne scored a career-high 3 goals in 23 appearances during the [[2023–24 Wellington Phoenix FC season|2023–24 season]].

During the [[2024–25 Wellington Phoenix FC season|2024–25 season]], Payne made 20 appearances in the league. He scored one goal during the season, scoring in a 2–0 win against [[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]] at [[HBF Park]], [[Perth]], on 26 October 2024.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360466011/wellington-phoenix-beat-perth-glory-first-win-league-men-season|title=Wellington Phoenix beat Perth Glory for first win of A-League Men season|date=27 October 2024|access-date=29 May 2026|website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|first=Andrew|last=Voerman}}</ref> On 17 December 2024, Payne signed a new three-year contract with the Phoenix, until the end of the 2027–28 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/all-whites-fullback-sticks-with-the-nix/|title=All Whites fullback sticks with the Nix|date=17 December 2024|access-date=29 December 2024|website=[[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]]}}</ref>

In the [[2025–26 Wellington Phoenix FC season|2025–26 season]], Payne made 14 appearances in the A-League Men and 2 appearances in the [[Australia Cup]]. On 26 October 2025, Payne suffered a broken collarbone in a 2–1 win against the Brisbane Roar in Wellington.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360867307/wellington-phoenix-defender-tim-payne-miss-first-two-derbies-and-all-whites-tour-major-injury-blow|title=Wellington Phoenix defender Tim Payne to miss first two derbies and All Whites tour in major injury blow|first=Phillip|last=Rollo|website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=28 October 2025|access-date=29 May 2026}}</ref>

==International career==
Payne represented New Zealand at [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|Under-17]] level. He played 90 minutes in each of his sides four matches at the [[2011 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] in Mexico.

In May 2012, Payne received a call-up from [[Ricki Herbert]] to the [[New Zealand men's national football team|senior national team]] alongside fellow youngster and U-17 teammate [[Cameron Howieson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nzfootball.co.nz/index.php?id=11&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=1649&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=10&cHash=df16549d5a|title=Herbert includes Payne and Howieson for World Cup qualifiers|date=15 May 2012|publisher=[[New Zealand Football]]|accessdate=27 May 2012}}</ref> He made his first appearance in a 1–0 win against [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]] on 26 May 2012, coming on as a substitute for [[Leo Bertos]] and playing the final 15 minutes of the match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzfootball.co.nz/index.php?id=11&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=1668&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=10&cHash=4954aa8b2e|title=All Whites beat Honduras in Dallas|date=27 May 2012|publisher=[[New Zealand Football]]|accessdate=27 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530012143/http://www.nzfootball.co.nz/index.php?id=11&tx_ttnews[tt_news]=1668&tx_ttnews[backPid]=10&cHash=4954aa8b2e|archivedate=30 May 2012}}</ref> He subsequently made an appearance off the bench in the OFC Nations Cup 2012. Payne was named in New Zealand's team for the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympics]].

On 30 March 2026, Payne received his 50th cap for the ''All Whites'' in a 4–1 win over [[Chile national football team|Chile]] as part of the [[2026 FIFA Series (men's matches)|2026 FIFA Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/164289?newsfeedId=1275608|title=All Whites Defeat Chile To Make History At Eden Park In FIFA Series|date=30 March 2026|access-date=31 March 2026|website=[[New Zealand Football]]}}</ref> With this win, New Zealand achieved their first ever win against a South American national team.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Burgess |first=Michael |date=30 March 2026|title=All Whites get Fifa World Cup boost with emphatic Chile victory |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/all-whites/all-whites-v-chile-live-updates-mens-fifa-series-eden-park/DE7ICBAFDVBATPQE36H6Q6DI7Q/ |access-date=2026-03-30 |website=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |language=en-NZ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Voerman |first=Andrew |title=All Whites break South American duck with morale-boosting win over 10-man Chile |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360952594/all-whites-break-south-american-duck-morale-boosting-win-over-10-man-chile |date=30 March 2026|access-date=2026-03-30 |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref>

On 14 May 2026, Payne was announced to be in the New Zealand squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=New Zealand Squad Named for FIFA World Cup 2026 |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/165753?newsfeedId=1275608&newsfeedPageNum=1 |access-date=2026-05-28 |website=www.nzfootball.co.nz}}</ref>

==Personal life==
On 28 May 2026, Payne became the target of a viral social media campaign by Argentinian [[influencer]] Valen Scarsini, who directed his followers to support Tim Payne specifically as the "least known" player at the World Cup.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rollo |first=Phillip |date=2026-05-28 |title=FIFA World Cup: How a viral campaign made All Whites defender Tim Payne an unexpected star |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360984943/fifa-world-cup-how-viral-campaign-made-all-whites-defender-tim-payne-unexpected-star |access-date=2026-05-28 |website=Stuff |language=en}}</ref> As a result, Payne's [[Instagram]] follower account grew from under 5,000 to more than 550,000 in less than a day.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sherry |first=Samuel |title='Legend of Tim Payne': Argentine influencer makes All Whites defender a cult hero |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/all-whites/world-cup-argentine-influencer-el-scarsos-video-makes-all-whites-defender-tim-payne-an-online-star/ETZVXGEMAZDJHENGEWJ7EZC63I/ |access-date=2026-05-28 |website=NZ Herald |language=en-NZ}}</ref> Within three days, he had reached more than 3.2 million followers, making his Instagram account the most followed football-related page from New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Limm |first=Nathan |title='Crazy 48 hours': All White thanks fans as his global fame soars |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/all-whites/tim-payne-all-white-defender-addresses-his-new-legion-of-fans-after-instagram-blow-up/NEZSYZABJNBRXFJ4ZHUUFO54RU/ |access-date=2026-05-28 |website=NZ Herald |language=en-NZ}}</ref> In response, Payne posted a video thanking Valen and his new fans for his new found fame, saying "I just wanted to also express that I'm very grateful to be representing my country and I appreciate all the love from all around the world".

As of 6 June, Payne has over 5 million followers on his Instagram.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Voerman |first=Andrew |date=2026-06-06 |title=What’s it like being Tim Payne? All White’s first interview since social media boom shows where his focus is ahead of World Cup |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360988750/whats-it-being-tim-payne-all-whites-first-interview-social-media-boom-shows-where-his-focus-ahead |access-date=2026-06-06 |website=Stuff |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title='I have my notifications turned off': Tim Payne speaks on newfound stardom |url=https://www.1news.co.nz/2026/06/06/i-have-my-notifications-turned-off-tim-payne-speaks-on-newfound-stardom/ |access-date=2026-06-06 |website=1News |language=en}}</ref>

